Psychology of Overlicitation: Why Do We Give More Money?
At the auction, buyers tend to give more money, overestimate the goods.
This well-known and seemingly irrational behavior has been discovered by neuro-economics researchers at the University of New York.
According to a study published in Science, people don’t want to fall under a type of competition, such as eBay’s auction, so they pay too high a price.
The study tried to map the e-play – neurosystemal pattern using experimental auctions.
One of the volunteers was lotteryd, the other group played an auction, while the functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) method examined the active brain areas of experimental subjects.
In both games, the participants could win money, but during the auction game - in which the other party's over-licitation - the complex under the striatum, under the brain corrugated, was intensively operational when the game was lost.
This brain area plays a role in the nervous system’s “remuneration” mechanism.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price can be explained by avoiding the intense reaction of striatum.
In order to support their theory, the members of the research group also carried out a financial follow-up investigation.
In this three groups have been lit against a partner in different circumstances.
With the control group, they simply reported how much the real value of the product in question and they had their bets.
In addition, another group has promised that if they win out of the game, they will get another $15.
The third group, however, received just $15 before auction, but the members of the group lost this money in case of a losing auction.
Thus, the difference between the two groups was that for one of them the winnings, the loss was emphasized for the other.
However, as evidenced by the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the team who played against loss were willing to hold a higher stake than the control and absorption group.
“These results cannot be derived from the theory of any previously existing economy.
It has been explained by the joy of victory and the risk-taking of auctioning phenomena.
Only neurological imaging methods helped to resolve the contradiction between these two theories, so that we have now reached a third explanation,” Andrew Schotter, a professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we contact a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death.
The number of hepatitis-infected people at home can be increased to one hundred times, but only seven thousand are treated, for which reason: patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is called a collection of infectious liver products caused by various viruses.
In their symptoms, there are many similarities, characteristic of inflammation of the liver and yellowness, but their pathogens and diseases are different from each other.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the nutrient channel (e.g. infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (swelling, vaginal discharge, swallowing).
Travelers should be protected against A and B virus, with no vaccine against C.
Hepatitis Symptoms occur two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal pain, nausea.
Then it develops on the skin and on the whites of the eye, the stool becomes clear, the urine becomes dark, and healing can last for two to three weeks.
One million people worldwide die in a more severe type of disease, liver cancer and liver sugar caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only every tenth infected will receive medication.
Hepatitis C may also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it may also lead to liver cancer.
Most infected people don’t even know about their disease because the pathogen destroys the liver’s cells thoroughly, and in many cases only in 20-30 years the first symptoms occur.
Thus, it is very important to early prevention, to carry out regular screening tests.
In three groups, the average number of such diseases is much more than the average: between people who have had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
The number of people infected with chronic hepatitis C virus can currently be 200 million in the world.
Since the disease can already be detected by a routine laboratory test, it is worth turning to your home doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
In time, recognizing the disease can be cured, the virus can be removed from the body, thus eliminating infection and preventing cancer from developing.
September 30 is the world day of hepatitis, which was first held in 2004 by patient organisations throughout the world.
Its goal is to draw attention to the importance of chronic hepatitis, causes of development and early recognition of the disease.
